\maketitle

$\bullet$ A $dg$-category, $T,$ admits a \emph{smooth categorical compactification} if there exists a smooth and proper $dg$-category, $\mathcal{C}$, and a quasi-functor, $$F: \mathcal{C} \rightarrow \mathcal{T},$$ such that extension of scalars, $$F^{*}: Perf(\mathcal{C}) \rightarrow Perf(\mathcal{T})$$ is a localization up to direct summands and has kernel generated by one object. 

$\bullet$Thm (Neeman) For compactly generated triangulated categories, $\mathfrak{T}$ and $\mathcal{S}$, and an exact functor, $F:\mathfrak{T} \rightarrow \mathcal{S}$, commuting with small direct sums and preserving compact objects, TFAE:

(i) The induced functor, $$F^{c}: \mathfrak{T}^{c} \rightarrow \mathcal{S}^{c},$$ is a localization up to direct summands. 

(ii) $F: \mathfrak{T} \rightarrow \mathcal{S}$ is a localization and it's kernel is generated (as a localizing subcategory) by it's intersection with $\mathfrak{T}^{c}$

$\bullet$ A $dg$- functor, $\Phi : \mathcal{A} \rightarrow \mathcal{B}$ between small $dg$-categories is a \emph{homological epimorphism} if extension of scalars, $$\Phi^{*} : \mathcal{D}(\mathcal{A}) \rightarrow \mathcal{D}(\mathcal B)$$ is a localization. 

$\bullet$ Prop (Efimov?) TFAE:

(i) $\Phi$ is a homological epimorphism

(ii) restriction of scalars, $\Phi _{*} : \mathcal{D} ( \mathcal B ) \rightarrow \mathcal D ( \mathcal A ) ,$ is quasi-fully-faithful. 

(iii) For all $X,Y \in Ob (\mathcal B ),$ the morphism: $$Hom_{\mathcal B} (X, \Phi (-) ) \otimes^{\mathbb L}_{\mathcal A} Hom_{\mathcal B} (\Phi (-) , Y) \rightarrow Hom_{\mathcal B} (X,Y)$$ is an isomorphism in $\mathcal D (k)$.

(iv) For all $X,Y \in \mathcal B,$ the natural map, $$Hom_{\mathcal B} (X,Y) \rightarrow \mathbb R Hom_{\mathcal A} (\Phi_{*} h_{X},\Phi_{*} h_{Y})$$ is an isomorphism in $\mathcal D (k)$.

(v) the natural morphism: $$( \Phi \otimes \Phi ^{op} )^{*}I_{\mathcal{A}} \rightarrow I_{\mathcal B },$$ is an isomorphism in $\mathcal D ( \mathcal B \otimes \mathcal B ^{op})$.


$\bullet$ Efimov calls $\Phi : \mathcal A \rightarrow B $ a \emph{localization} if$\Phi ^{*} : Perf (\mathcal A ) \rightarrow Perf (\mathcal B )$ is a localization up to direct summands. 


$\bullet$ Prop (Efimov ?) TFAE:

(i) $\Phi$ is a localization. 

(ii) $\Phi$ is a homological epimorphism and the kernel of $\mathcal D ( \mathcal A ) \rightarrow \mathcal D (\mathcal B ) $ is generated by it's intersection with $Perf( \mathcal A )$

$\bullet$ Efimov uses an \emph{Auslander-type construction} to construct compactifications of dg categories of perfect sheaves on notherian schemes over perfect fields. 

$\bullet$ Auslander construction to be summarized....

$\bullet$ We'll throw in some gillet and soule definitions now...

$\bullet$ A proper map of schemes, $f: X' \rightarrow X,$ is an \emph{envelope} when for all fields, $F,$ all $F$-valued points of $X$ lift to$X'.$

$\bullet$ When $X$ is defined over a field of characteristic 0, $X$ always admits a smooth projective envelope. 

$\bullet$ A \emph{hyperenvelope} is a map, $p:X_{\bullet} \rightarrow Y_{\bullet},$ of simplicial schemes which is proper in each degree and which is a hypercover for the Grothendeick topology in which the covering maps ar envelopes. 

Equivalently, a hyperenvelope is a level-wise proper map of simplicial schemes such that for all fields, $F,$ the map, $X_{\bullet}(F) \rightarrow Y_{\bullet}(F),$ of simplicial sets is a trivial kan fibration.

$\bullet$ Let $f: Y_{\bullet} \rightarrow X_{\bullet}$ be a map of simplicial schemes. A \emph{hyperenvelope}, $ h: \tilde{f} \rightarrow f$ is a morphism of arrows of simplicial schemes with components hyperenvelopes. 

$\bullet$ (definition of compactly supported $K$ theory)

